anyways i struggle a lot with articulating my thoughts so i hope this was understandable! i’ve just been frustrated with a lot of the misinformation i’ve been receiving in my messages.

the point is, there is misinformation everywhere. to say someone is completely healthy, but there is a huge gap since the last time they did a body checkup, is a baseless assumption at best. and, most importantly, trust the evidence. Google can show you what you need.

our organs don’t deteriorate that quickly (if we were confirmed to be healthy since birth) unless it is genetic or congenital. it is a buildup of many factors, over the years, that in turn makes it irreversible.

the human body, our body, is fascinating. it has evolved so much to sustain our survival. to be able to beat it and cause severe, life threatening illness takes some time, in which interventions can be done if we regularly check our body’s condition, and what it’s telling us.

in fact, evidence-based medicine is one of the major things we consider when making medical decisions. if the evidence favours a certain treatment for a certain age group, we go with the safest option with the best evidence available. we should do the same. especially now.

the practice of evidence-based medicine is imperative. when we’re investigating a case, we need the evidence in order to persecute the suspect. similarly, VALID and APPRAISED clinical trials are the evidence of the medical field, done with real people and real statistics.

of course, there are social factors to be considered like the cost and whether people can afford these checkups in the first place. as a medical student who sees financial struggle from patients often, i’m so sorry that the system has failed to give u what is a basic human right.

some aren’t actually perfectly healthy, it’s just undetected and undiagnosed until it’s too late, and made to look like an effect of something people want to convince others to stay away from. essentially, once again, to push their own selfish narratives (that can be detrimental)

i think this is why people can use this to push their own narratives to perpetuate fear and spread misinformation in medicine. you can have an outwardly perfectly healthy person with an undiagnosed medical problem bc they don’t check for them.

it’s difficult to determine cause and effect without prior checkups as a baseline for their health. different people have different standards on what healthy is, when you consider factors such as chronic illnesses and our own reservoir of medical knowledge to decide.

the truth is, a lot of diseases don’t show up, or are subtle, until it becomes severe. patient perception is also important as the person in question might not even realise they have an issue because it’s the norm for them.

i think the difference between being previously healthy and having undiagnosed diseases should be discerned. you assume a person is healthy bc they have no symptoms even without the evidence a body checkup will provide.
